Here’s a simple example using React Native’s `fetch` with a timeout to handle unresponsive clients:

javascript
const fetchClientDataWithTimeout = async (url, timeout = 10000) => {
  const controller = new AbortController();
  const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), timeout);

  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, { signal: controller.signal });
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    return await response.json();
  } catch (error) {
    if (error.name === 'AbortError') {
      console.log('Client reply timed out');
      return null;
    }
    throw error;
  }
};

// Usage:
fetchClientDataWithTimeout('https://client-api.com/data')
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(err => console.error('Error:', err));

This snippet includes a 10-second timeout to prevent indefinite waiting for client responses.
